### Animation

CSS3 animations allows animation of most HTML elements without using JavaScript or Flash! 
Modulr.css has included a small animation module. You can always extend the core animation 
module by creating your own. You can trigger modulr.css animations using direct or parent-child 
hover behavior modifier, but you can also use javascript to trigger animations.

When applying animation to an element you can use .*animation-name class direct on that element.

Parent-child animations are mostly triggered by parents hover behavior. eg: .hover-animate-children 
class is used on a parent element, .mouseenter-*animation-name for when mouse enters an element, 
and .mouseleave-*animation-name for when mouse leaves an element are used on child elements of a
parent element with .hover-animate-children class modifier. See example below.

##### html
----------

```
<!-- Animate an element -->
<div class="move-in-down fast">Move in down fast</div>

<!-- Animate an child on parent's hover -->
<div class="hover-animate-children">
  <span class="mouseenter-fade-out-down mouseleave-fade-in-up fast">
    Animated Child
  </span>
</div>
```

##### Animation Speed

You can specify speed of an animation using one of the speed class modifiers .slow for slow {2.2s}, 
.normal for normal {1s}, .medium for medium {0.6s}, .fast for fast {0.3s} and .faster for fastest {0.15s} 
You can also create your own animation speed modifiers by looking at the example in animation core module.

##### Let's see how we can use a simple on hover animation.

##### html
----------

```
<a href="#" class="btn blue hover-scale-out medium">Hover Scale Out</a>

<a href="#" class="btn purple overflow-hidden hover-animate-children">
  Hover Animate Child 
  <span class="inline-block mouseenter-fade-out-down mouseleave-fade-in-up fast">
    Animate Child
  </span>
</a>
```

As you can see in the code example above, we're using .mouseenter-*animation-name and .mouseleave-*animation-name 
inside our .hover-animate-children parent element. With this two classes you can specify when and what kind of 
animation should be triggered on .hover-animate-children:hover


##### Let's use parent-child animations with some of the core modifiers to create a cool button effect

##### html
----------

```
<div class="relative overflow-hidden pull-left hover-animate-children ">
  <a href="#" class="btn purple absolute
    mouseenter-move-out-down mouseleave-move-in-up faster">
    Hover Over Me
  </a>
  <a href="#" class="btn blue 
    mouseenter-move-in-down mouseleave-move-out-up faster">
    Hover Over Me
  </a>
</div>
```

As you can see in the code above, we've created a .hover-animate-children wrapper with a relative position 
and overflow:hidden. Inside our wrapper we have two buttons which will react to our on parent:hover > trigger children 
animation behavior. First button has absolute position, this will allow us to place two buttons one on top of the other. 
The animation classes are pretty self explanatory, .mousenter-*animation-name will trigger the animation-name when mouse 
enters the element and .mouseleave-*animation-name will trigger the animation-name when mouse leaves the element.


